   <abstract >This dissertation, The Rise of the Editress: Women's Editorship in the Literary Marketplace of the Long Nineteenth Century, explores the role of gender in editorial labor during the long nineteenth century. I focus on the "editress," a term used throughout the nineteenth century to reference women in editorial positions. Like the figure of the "poetess" the editress is treated differently from her male counterparts, having to simultaneously navigate editorial authority and traditional gender roles. However, critical analysis of editorship has lagged significantly behind studies of authorship, and much of the limited work on nineteenth-century editing focuses primarily on male editors. My scholarship resides at the intersections of literary studies and book history in order to interrogate the gendering of literary labor and the British marketplace. To investigate the role of the editress, I study the careers of women across the century and across genres—Anna Letitia Barbauld, Sarah Stickney Ellis, Caroline Norton, and Mary Elizabeth Braddon who edited anthologies, literary annuals, and periodicals, respectively. Using what I am calling the "editor function," after Michel Foucault's "author function," I analyze both the editress's construction and her reception. These case studies help formulate a more complete picture of the editress and to access her role in the larger literary marketplace. I trace a trend of increased visibility of the editress through the century, which ultimately boosted her authority and, at the same time, made her a target of criticism.</abstract>
